RQ1 b.

df <- employments %>%
  left_join(members, by = "m_id") %>%
  mutate(age = 2025 - birth_dt) %>%  # Calculate age
  filter(!is.na(age))  # Remove missing age values
# Categorize employees into 5 age groups
df <- df %>%
  
  mutate(age = 2025 - birth_dt,
         hire_year = year(hire_dt),
         age_group = case_when(
           age < 30 ~ "Under 30",
           age >= 30 & age < 40 ~ "30-39",
           age >= 40 & age < 50 ~ "40-49",
           age >= 50 & age < 60 ~ "50-59",
           age >= 60 ~ "60+"
         ))
# Count the number of employees in each age group per year
age_group_trends <- df %>%
  group_by(hire_year, age_group) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop")
# Define colors for better readability
age_colors <- c("Under 30" = "#AEDFF7",  # Light Blue
                "30-39" = "#FFCBA4",  # Soft Orange
                "40-49" = "#B0E57C",  # Light Green
                "50-59" = "#FFB6C1",  # Pastel Pink
                "60+" = "#D4A5FF")  # Soft Purple
# Create the trend visualization
ggplot(age_group_trends, aes(x = hire_year, y = count, color = age_group, group = age_group)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = age_colors) +
  labs(title = "Age Group Trends Over Time (Statewide)",
       subtitle = "Tracking changes in workforce composition",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Employees",
       color = "Age Group") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85"),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `linewidth` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.

Based on the chart, the overall age group distribution increased after 1980, but most age groups experienced a major decline after 2008. Following this drop, the trends fluctuated but remained relatively steady until 2020 and beyond. Employees in the 30-39 age group saw a significant rise after 2008, reaching their peak around 2018, before experiencing a sharp decline until 2023. Similarly, employees under 30 had a rapid increase in 2018, marking the highest recorded number of employees approximately 2,500 employee in history. However, this was followed by a significant drop in the following years. These trends suggest that while the workforce initially grew, recruitment or retention challenges may have led to a decrease in younger employees after 2018. Meanwhile, other age groups have shown more stability, but agencies should monitor workforce aging trends to prepare for future staffing needs.

Age Trends by Agency

# Count total employees per agency
top_20_agencies <- df %>%
  count(employer_name, name = "total_employees") %>%
  arrange(desc(total_employees)) %>%
  top_n(20, total_employees)  # Get top 20 agencies

df_top20 <- df %>%

age_group_by_top20 <- df_top20 %>%
  group_by(employer_name, age_group) %>%

                "60+" = "#D4A5FF")  # Soft Purple

The chart shows that some agencies have a higher concentration of older employees (50+), while others have more younger employees (Under 30 and 30-39). A few agencies have a balanced distribution across all age groups, while others are dominated by either older or younger employees. Agencies with older employees (50+) have a noticeably larger share, while agencies with a strong Under 30 workforce show higher numbers but with variation across agencies. The 30-39 age group appears consistently strong across multiple agencies, while the 40-49 age group varies.

# Ensure total_service is numeric
df <- df %>%

# Calculate average years of service per year
service_trends_overall <- df %>%
  group_by(hire_year) %>%

  arrange(hire_year)

service_trends_by_agency <- df %>%

        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85"),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

The line chart above shows that the aberage years of service increased sharply after 1960 but experienced a mojor decline around 1980. The highest recorded years of service appear before the decline which means that employees hired in earlier years tended to stay longer. After 2008, the average years of service gradually decreased which showing a possible shift in retention patterns or workforce turnover.

RQ1 d.

# Ensure hire and termination dates are in Date format
df <- df %>%
  mutate(hire_dt = as.Date(hire_dt),
         term_dt = as.Date(term_dt),
         hire_year = year(hire_dt),
         term_year = year(term_dt))

# Count total separations per year
separations <- df %>%
  filter(!is.na(term_dt)) %>%
  group_by(term_year) %>%
  summarise(separations = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  rename(year = term_year)

# Count total employees per year
total_employees <- df %>%
  group_by(hire_year) %>%
  summarise(total_employees = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  rename(year = hire_year)

# Merge datasets and calculate separation & retention rates
separation_trends <- left_join(separations, total_employees, by = "year") %>%
  mutate(separation_rate = (separations / total_employees) * 100,
         retention_rate = 100 - separation_rate)
# Convert to long format for ggplot
separation_trends_long <- separation_trends %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(separation_rate, retention_rate),
               names_to = "metric",
               values_to = "rate")

# Define custom colors
custom_colors <- c("separation_rate" = "#E74C3C",  # Red for separation
                   "retention_rate" = "#2ECC71")   # Green for retention

# Create a visually appealing line graph
ggplot(separation_trends_long, aes(x = year, y = rate, color = metric)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.5, alpha = 0.8) +
  scale_color_manual(values = custom_colors, labels = c("Separation Rate", "Retention Rate")) +
  labs(title = "Separation & Retention Trends Over Time",
       subtitle = "Tracking workforce stability",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Rate (%)",
       color = "Metric") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "top",
        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85"),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

The chart above shows that the separation rate fluctuated over the years, with noticeable increases and decreases at different points. After 2008, there was a sharp rise in separations, followed by fluctuations but a relatively steady trend in later years. Meanwhile, the retention rate followed the opposite pattern, decreasing when separations increased and stabilizing when separations declined. The trends indicate that at certain periods, more employees left, while at other times, retention efforts were stronger that is keeping employees in their positions.

# Calculate retention rate per agency
agency_retention <- df %>%
  group_by(employer_name) %>%
  summarise(separations = sum(!is.na(term_dt)),
            total_employees = n(),
            retention_rate = (1 - (separations / total_employees)) * 100,
            .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(desc(retention_rate))

# Select top 20 agencies with highest retention
top_20_retention <- agency_retention %>% top_n(20, retention_rate)

# Create a horizontal bar chart
ggplot(top_20_retention, aes(x = retention_rate, y = reorder(employer_name, retention_rate))) +
  geom_col(fill = "#E74") +  # Green for retention
  geom_text(aes(label = round(retention_rate, 1)), hjust = 1.2, color = "white", size = 5) +  # Add labels
  labs(title = "Top 20 Agencies with Highest Retention Rate",
       x = "Retention Rate (%)",
       y = "Agency") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85"),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

From the chart above, top agencies have consistently high retention rates. This is meaning that employees tend to stay longer in these organizations. The highest-ranked agencies have a perfect retention, while others in the top 20 still maintain strong employee stability. The differences between agencies suggest that some organizations have better long-term employee retention than others. This is could be affected by workplace conditions, policies, or job stability.

RQ1 e.

# Ensure hire and termination dates are in Date format
df <- df %>%
  mutate(hire_dt = as.Date(hire_dt),
         term_dt = as.Date(term_dt),
         hire_year = year(hire_dt),
         term_year = year(term_dt))

# Identify employees who transferred (left one agency and joined another)
transfers <- df %>%
  filter(!is.na(term_dt) & !is.na(hire_dt) & hire_dt > term_dt) %>%
  group_by(hire_year) %>%
  summarise(transfers = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  rename(year = hire_year)

# Count total employees per year
total_employees <- df %>%
  group_by(hire_year) %>%
  summarise(total_employees = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  rename(year = hire_year)

# Merge datasets and calculate transfer rate
transfer_trends <- left_join(transfers, total_employees, by = "year") %>%
  mutate(transfer_rate = (transfers / total_employees) * 100)
# Create a visually appealing line graph
ggplot(transfer_trends, aes(x = year, y = transfer_rate)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.5, color = "#3498DB", alpha = 0.8) +  # Smooth line (blue)
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "#2980B9", alpha = 0.9) +   # Highlight points
  labs(title = "Employee Transfer Trends Over Time",
       subtitle = "Tracking movement between agencies",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Transfer Rate (%)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85"),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

The chart shows that the number of employee transfers gradually decline over the years.
